    {
      "id": "RQ-0004",
      "status": "done",
      "title": "Forward the documented upstream env/config surface to agent-browser",
      "description": "Principles violated: A) KISS, F) Fail fast, G) Least astonishment, J) Consistency/Integrity.\n\nWhy it matters: the child-process environment is restricted to a tiny allowlist plus `AI_GATEWAY_*` and `XDG_*`. That strips standard upstream `agent-browser` configuration and auth inputs such as `AGENT_BROWSER_CONFIG`, `AGENT_BROWSER_SESSION_NAME`, and related provider credentials, so a package-first global install cannot rely on the normal upstream env-driven setup even though the extension is supposed to stay thin and close to upstream behavior.\n\nMinimal proposed fix: expand the child env policy to forward the documented upstream configuration/auth variables needed for normal `agent-browser` operation, plus a curated set of provider credential variables. Preserve the existing secret-redaction behavior for tool progress/details so forwarding these vars does not leak them back into Pi.\n\nAcceptance criteria: `npm test` stays green; a focused env test proves the child sees documented config/auth vars such as `AGENT_BROWSER_CONFIG`, `AGENT_BROWSER_SESSION_NAME`, and `AGENT_BROWSER_ACTION_POLICY`, while unrelated secrets still remain filtered from tool updates/details.",
      "priority": "high",
      "tags": [
        "maintenance",
        "operability",
        "passthrough"
      ],
      "scope": [
        "extensions/agent-browser/lib/process.ts",
        "test/agent-browser.test.ts",
        "agent-browser --help",
        "npx tsx"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "path: extensions/agent-browser/lib/process.ts:25-71 :: the inherited env allowlist omits the standard upstream `AGENT_BROWSER_*` surface and any provider-specific credential vars.",
        "path: extensions/agent-browser/lib/process.ts:107-133 :: `buildAgentBrowserProcessEnv` drops every env key outside that allowlist before spawning `agent-browser`.",
        "workflow: agent-browser --help :: the current installed CLI documents upstream environment-driven configuration such as `AGENT_BROWSER_CONFIG`, `AGENT_BROWSER_SESSION_NAME`, `AGENT_BROWSER_ACTION_POLICY`, screenshot/download settings, and provider-backed workflows.",
        "workflow: npx tsx <<'EOF' ... buildAgentBrowserProcessEnv({... AGENT_BROWSER_CONFIG, AGENT_BROWSER_SESSION_NAME, AGENT_BROWSER_ACTION_POLICY, BROWSERBASE_API_KEY, AI_GATEWAY_API_KEY ...}) ... EOF :: observed `hasAgentBrowserConfig = false`, `hasAgentBrowserSessionName = false`, `hasAgentBrowserActionPolicy = false`, `hasBrowserbaseApiKey = false`, while `hasAiGatewayApiKey = true`."
      ],
      "plan": [
        "Define the minimum upstream env/config surface the wrapper must preserve to stay thin and package-first friendly.",
        "Update `buildAgentBrowserProcessEnv` to forward that documented surface and add regression coverage for config/auth/provider envs.",
        "Confirm tool progress/details still redact sensitive values after the broader env passthrough.",
        "Verify by running `npm test` and a focused env probe that confirms the child process receives the intended upstream config/auth vars."
      ],
      "notes": [],
