    {
      "id": "RQ-0026",
      "status": "done",
      "title": "Make stale temp-root pruning robust to PID reuse",
      "description": "Principles violated: E) Make bugs hard to write, H) Operational hygiene, J) Consistency/Integrity.\n\nWhy it matters: stale-root pruning now trusts only the recorded PID plus UID to decide whether an owned temp root is still live. If a crashed root's PID gets reused by an unrelated live process, the stale root becomes effectively unprunable and can linger indefinitely instead of aging out on the next run. Under repeated crashes or long-lived hosts, that leaves hidden temp artifacts behind forever.\n\nMinimal proposed fix: extend the ownership marker with a stronger liveness token such as process start time, boot/session nonce, or renewable lease content, and require that stronger token before treating a stale root as still alive.\n\nAcceptance criteria: a backdated temp root whose marker PID has been reused by a different live process is pruned on the next temp-root acquisition; live current roots still remain protected; verify `npm run verify` stays green.",
      "priority": "medium",
      "tags": [
        "maintenance",
        "temp-files",
        "cleanup",
