      "title": "Add first-run doctor for PATH and source conflicts",
      "description": "Opportunity type: UX improvement. The product is package-first and the docs repeatedly warn that users must install upstream `agent-browser` separately, keep exactly one active extension source, and avoid duplicate `agent_browser` registrations. Today the extension has a strong missing-binary error, but there is no single first-run diagnostic flow that checks PATH, targeted upstream version, or conflicting checkout/package installs before a user hits runtime friction. Why it matters: a lightweight doctor flow would shorten time-to-first-success, reduce support/debug churn, and make package-first onboarding much safer. Proposed approach: ship a minimal read-only maintainer-and-user facing diagnostic entrypoint, distinct from upstream `agent-browser doctor`, that checks `agent-browser` presence/version from the canonical capability baseline, inspects how Pi resolves this extension, flags multi-source conflicts when Pi exposes enough source metadata, and prints exact remediation steps; expand later with optional packaged/install-mode checks. Risks and mitigations: keep it read-only by default, do not mutate Pi settings, and scope it to observed failure modes so the wrapper stays thin. Acceptance criteria: one documented package-level command reports missing binary, version drift, and duplicate source conflicts with actionable fixes; release docs and README point to it; deterministic tests cover the expected failure messages.",
